"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.314105104/asset/images/105104fig15.jpeg" height="895" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span> Pylephlebitis in a 50-year-old man with symptoms of abdominal sepsis. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows a thrombosed right portal vein (arrow) and multiple abscesses (arrowheads) in hepatic segment IV, findings indicative of pylephlebitis. The abscesses resolved after the administration of culture-tested systemic antibiotics. (Courtesy of Philip W. Ralls, MD, USC Los Angeles County Hospital, Los Angeles, Calif.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.314105104&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.314105104/asset/images/105104fig16a.jpeg" height="1066" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.314105104&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.314105104/asset/images/105104fig16b.jpeg" height="1066" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.314105104&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.314105104/asset/images/105104fig16c.jpeg" height="1012" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16c</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.314105104&amp;id=fig16c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.314105104/asset/images/105104fig17.jpeg" height="1280" width="1053" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span> Calcifications at the splenomesenteric venous confluence in a 61-year-old man with viral hepatitis–induced cirrhosis and portal venous hypertension. Coronal contrast-enhanced maximum intensity projection CT image shows nodular and linear foci of high attenuation (arrowheads) at the splenomesenteric venous confluence.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.314105104&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.314105104/asset/images/105104fig18a.jpeg" height="940" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.314105104&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.314105104/asset/images/105104fig18b.jpeg" height="939" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.314105104&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure><